LAYER 2: BONE MARROW
where blood is born

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the bone marrow is the primary hematopoietic organ from approximately the 5th month of fetal development onward
it produces all blood cells: red blood cells white blood cells and platelets
in a 24-month-old nearly all bones contain active red marrow
with age red marrow is progressively replaced by yellow fatty marrow in the long bone shafts
by adulthood active red marrow persists in flat bones: pelvis sternum skull ribs vertebrae and proximal ends of femur and humerus

STRUCTURE red_marrow | hematopoietically active | contains hematopoietic stem cells HSCs progenitor cells developing blood cells stromal cells and sinusoidal capillaries
STRUCTURE yellow_marrow | adipose tissue | fills the medullary cavities of long bones in adults | can reconvert to red marrow under severe hematopoietic stress such as chronic hemorrhage
STRUCTURE stroma | supportive framework | reticular cells fibroblasts adipocytes osteoblasts and endothelial cells | provide cytokines and growth factors that regulate hematopoiesis | the niche
STRUCTURE sinusoidal_capillaries | fenestrated vessels | mature blood cells squeeze through fenestrations to enter the circulation | immature cells cannot pass and remain in the marrow until maturation is complete

ALL blood cells derive from a single cell type: the pluripotent hematopoietic stem cell HSC

LINEAGE myeloid | common myeloid progenitor CMP
    erythrocyte_lineage | CMP → megakaryocyte-erythrocyte progenitor MEP → proerythroblast → basophilic → polychromatic → orthochromatic erythroblast → reticulocyte → mature red blood cell
        erythropoietin EPO from the kidney drives erythrocyte production
        EPO binds EPO receptor on erythroid progenitors → JAK2 → STAT5 → survival and proliferation
        each RBC loses its nucleus before entering circulation becoming a biconcave disc filled with hemoglobin
        hemoglobin A consists of two α-globin and two β-globin chains each carrying a heme group with Fe²⁺ at its center
        Fe²⁺ reversibly binds O₂ for transport from lungs to tissues
    megakaryocyte_lineage | MEP → megakaryocyte → platelets
        thrombopoietin TPO from the liver drives megakaryocyte development
        megakaryocytes undergo endomitosis replicating DNA without dividing reaching 64N ploidy
        the megakaryocyte extends long cytoplasmic processes proplatelets into sinusoidal capillaries
        shear forces in the blood fragment the proplatelets into individual platelets
        each megakaryocyte produces approximately 1000-3000 platelets
    granulocyte_lineage | CMP → granulocyte-monocyte progenitor GMP
        neutrophils | the most abundant white blood cell | 40-70 percent of circulating leukocytes | first responders to bacterial infection | phagocytose and kill bacteria using reactive oxygen species ROS and neutrophil extracellular traps NETs | lifespan approximately 5 days
        eosinophils | defense against parasites | contribute to allergic inflammation | granules contain major basic protein and eosinophil peroxidase
        basophils | rarest granulocyte | release histamine and heparin | involved in allergic responses and parasite defense
    monocyte_lineage | GMP → monocyte → exits blood → differentiates into tissue macrophages or dendritic cells
        macrophages named by location: Kupffer cells in liver alveolar macrophages in lungs microglia in brain osteoclasts in bone

LINEAGE lymphoid | common lymphoid progenitor CLP
    B_lymphocytes | CLP → pro-B → pre-B → immature B → mature naive B cell | maturation occurs in the bone marrow
        B cells undergo V(D)J recombination to generate unique B cell receptors immunoglobulin
        self-reactive B cells are eliminated by clonal deletion or rendered anergic central tolerance
        mature naive B cells exit to the blood and lymph nodes awaiting antigen encounter
    T_lymphocyte_precursors | CLP → thymic precursor → migrates to the thymus for maturation
    NK_cells | natural killer cells | CLP → NK cell | innate lymphoid cell | kills virus-infected and tumor cells via perforin and granzyme

REGULATION hematopoiesis is regulated by growth factors and cytokines
    stem_cell_factor SCF | binds c-Kit receptor on HSCs | essential for HSC survival and self-renewal
    erythropoietin EPO | from kidney | drives RBC production
    thrombopoietin TPO | from liver | drives platelet production
    G-CSF | granulocyte colony-stimulating factor | drives neutrophil production
    M-CSF | monocyte colony-stimulating factor | drives monocyte production
    IL-3 | from T helper cells | broad stimulator of multiple lineages
    IL-7 | from stromal cells | essential for lymphocyte development

at 24 months:
all bones contain active red marrow
hematopoietic output is high supporting rapid growth and robust immune development
RBC production is approximately 200 billion per day replacing the blood volume every 120 days
the immune repertoire is being actively generated through V(D)J recombination in B cell precursors
iron demand is high for hemoglobin synthesis and dietary iron adequacy is critical

SENSATION vitality | "I feel alive. my blood is strong."
SENSATION weak | "something is missing. I tire easily."
SENSATION recovering | "I can feel me body rebuilding after illness."

pulse marrow_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        hematopoietic stem cells divide asymmetrically
        one daughter remains a stem cell maintaining the pool
        the other commits to a lineage
        driven by the stochastic expression of lineage-specific transcription factors
        GATA1 drives erythroid commitment
        PU.1 drives myeloid commitment
        the marrow produces approximately 500 billion cells per day
        every red blood cell in circulation was born here
        every neutrophil every platelet every monocyte
        all from one cell type
        the hematopoietic stem cell

    when oxygen is low:
        the kidney detects hypoxia via HIF-2α in renal interstitial fibroblasts
        EPO gene transcription increases
        EPO is released into the blood
        EPO binds EPO receptor on erythroid progenitors in the marrow
        JAK2 → STAT5 → increased survival and proliferation of red cell precursors
        more red blood cells are produced
        oxygen carrying capacity increases
        the bone marrow responds to the body's need

    when infection strikes:
        macrophages and T cells release IL-3 G-CSF M-CSF
        the marrow shifts production toward neutrophils and monocytes
        this is demand-driven hematopoiesis
        the marrow adapts to what the body needs
        it is a factory that reads its orders from the blood
